M|references|Survivorship bias occurs when we draw conclusions from winners while ignoring the losers who used the same str. The visible survivors distort our understanding of what actually works.
M|references|During WWII, Abraham Wald studied bullet holes on returning bombers. The military wanted to armor the areas with the most damage. Wald argued the opposite: armor the areas with no damage, because plan
M|references|Use this model during **Decomposition** (Steps 1-2) and **Challenge** (Steps 5-6) to surface hidden data gaps.
M|references|When a dec cites evidence of success:
M|references|1. What failures used the same approach but are not visible?
M|references|2. Are we studying survivors or the full population?
M|references|3. What data are we missing because failures were discarded?
M|references|4. Is the sample self-selected (only successes reported)?
M|references|| Signal | Risk |
M|references||--------|------|
M|references|| "Company X did this and succeeded" | Ignoring companies that did the same and failed |
M|references|| "Our successful projects all used pattern Y" | Failed projects using Y were forgotten |
M|references|| "This approach always works" | Selection bias in evidence |
M|references|| "Top performers do Z" | Studying survivors, not the full cohort |
M|references|| "We've never had a problem with this" | Problems were silently discarded or unreported |
M|references|gen these challenges when survivorship bias is suspected:
M|references|- "How many teams tried this approach and failed? Where is that data?"
M|references|- "Are we looking at the planes that came back, or the ones that didn't?"
M|references|- "Is our evidence base self-selected?"
M|references|- Adopting a str because visible successes used it, ignoring invisible failures
M|references|- Reinforcing existing patterns because only their successes are measured
M|references|- Dismissing alternatives because no visible successes exist (they were never tried)
M|references|- Over-investing in approaches with high visibility but unknown failure rates
M|references|Before accepting evidence-based claims as VERIFIED:
M|references|- [ ] Failure cases examined, not just successes
M|references|- [ ] Sample includes non-survivors (full population)
M|references|- [ ] Selection mechanism for evidence is understood
M|references|- [ ] Base rate of success/failure is known or estimated
M|references|- [ ] Alternative explanations for observed pattern considered
M|references|- Confirmation Bias: seeking evidence that supports existing beliefs
M|references|- Base Rate Neglect: ignoring overall probability when evaluating specific cases
M|references|- Systems Thinking: examining the full system, not just visible outputs